-de-France\n|Aisne\n| rowspan=\"5\" |{{#invoke:String|match|{{#invoke:wd|properties|normal+|Q87144163|P1603|sep=X}}|[^X]*$}}\n|280\n|44\n|263\n|136\n|-\n|Nord\n|937\n|270\n|634\n|228\n|-\n|Oise\n|434\n|70\n|409\n|196\n|-\n|Pas-de-Calais\n|446\n|104\n|334\n|92\n|-\n|Somme\n|359\n|76\n|233\n|110\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" |Ile-de-France\n|Paris\n| rowspan=\"8\" |12,108<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sortiraparis.com/news/coronavirus/articles/210162-coronavirus-update-on-the-situation-in-paris-and-ile-de-france-consultation-cent/lang/en|title=Coronavirus: update on the situation in Paris and \u00eele-de-France, consultation centers open|website=sortiraparis.com}}</ref>\n|3,181\n|841\n|2,005\n|839\n|-\n|Seine-et-Marne\n|782\n|208\n|779\n|213\n|-\n|Yvelines\n|1,042\n|191\n|685\n|250\n|-\n|Essonne\n|1,184\n|233\n|515\n|192\n|-\n|Hauts-de-Seine\n|1,974\n|434\n|1,415\n|463\n|-\n|Seine-Saint-Denis\n|1,597\n|251\n|929\n|480\n|-\n|Val-de-Marne\n|2,190\n|328\n|1,023\n|510\n|-\n|Val-d'Oise\n|911\n|179\n|962\n|353\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |Normandy\n|Calvados\n| rowspan=\"5\" |{{#invoke:String|match|{{#invoke:wd|properties|normal+|Q87144265|P1603|sep=X}}|[^X]*$}}\n|165\n|59\n|72\n|32\n|-\n|Eure\n|87\n|8\n|47\n|33\n|-\n|Manche\n|79\n|23\n|46\n|19\n|-\n|Orne\n|75\n|13\n|89\n|14\n|-\n|Seine-Maritime\n|335\n|107\n|258\n|90\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" |Nouvelle-Aquitaine\n|Charente\n| rowspan=\"12\" |{{#invoke:String|match|{{#invoke:wd|properties|normal+|Q87144289|P1603|sep=X}}|[^X]*$}}\n|10\n|4\n|30\n|8\n|-\n|Charente-Maritime\n|78\n|21\n|56\n|21\n|-\n|Corr\u00e8ze\n|39\n|10\n|34\n|12\n|-\n|Creuse\n|29\n|13\n|9\n|4\n|-\n|Dordogne\n|26\n|5\n|27\n|1\n|-\n|Gironde\n|281\n|81\n|338\n|60\n|-\n|Landes\n|25\n|13\n|31\n|9\n|-\n|Lot-et-Garonne\n|28\n|6\n|17\n|4\n|-\n|Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques\n|97\n|28\n|86\n|16\n|-\n|Deux-S\u00e8vres\n|38\n|12\n|19\n|9\n|-\n|Vienne\n|56\n|23\n|52\n|19\n|-\n|Haute-Vienne\n|68\n|13\n|43\n|11\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" |Occitanie\n|Ari\u00e8ge\n| rowspan=\"12\" |{{#invoke:String|match|{{#invoke:wd|properties|normal+|Q87144502|P1603|sep=X}}|[^X]*$}}\n|15\n|4\n|15\n|1\n|-\n|Aveyron\n|50\n|8\n|56\n|17\n|-\n|Gard\n|108\n|41\n|83\n|22\n|-\n|Haute-Garonne\n|250\n|97\n|228\n|26\n|-\n|Gers\n|25\n|4\n|20\n|8\n|-\n|H\u00e9rault\n|212\n|67\n|349\n|70\n|-\n|Lot\n|18\n|8\n|49\n|2\n|-\n|Loz\u00e8re\n|6\n|1\n|11\n|0\n|-\n|Hautes-Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es\n|68\n|6\n|43\n|7\n|-\n|Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Orientales\n|79\n|33\n|182\n|20\n|-\n|Tarn\n|45\n|20\n|49\n|9\n|-\n|Tarn-et-Garonne\n|19\n|10\n|11\n|3\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |Pays de la Loire\n|Loire-Atlantique\n| rowspan=\"5\" |{{#invoke:String|match|{{#invoke:wd|properties|normal+|Q87144323|P1603|sep=X}}|[^X]*$}}\n|289\n|70\n|210\n|60\n|-\n|Maine-et-Loire\n|194\n|54\n|233\n|49\n|-\n|Mayenne\n|74\n|14\n|30\n|17\n|-\n|Sarthe\n|143\n|21\n|110\n|24\n|-\n|Vend\u00e9e\n|72\n|21\n|58\n|19\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |Provence-Alpes-C\u00f4te-d'Azur\n|Alpes-de-Haute-Provence\n| rowspan=\"6\" |{{#invoke:String|match|{{#invoke:wd|properties|normal+|Q87144359|P1603|sep=X}}|[^X]*$}}\n|35\n|4\n|60\n|4\n|-\n|Hautes-Alpes\n|52\n|15\n|65\n|2\n|-\n|Alpes-Maritimes\n|278\n|83\n|231\n|63\n|-\n|Bouches-du-Rh\u00f4ne\n|1,089\n|267\n|1,167\n|160\n|-\n|Var\n|269\n|53\n|316\n|49\n|-\n|Vaucluse\n|81\n|19\n|107\n|21\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Subtotal France M\u00e9tropolitaine\n!90,312\n!31,119\n!6,961\n!24,739\n!8,581\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |French Guiana\n|28\n|9\n|1\n|13\n|0\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |Martinique\n|66\n|44\n|16\n|48\n|5\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |Saint Martin\n|11\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |Saint Barth\u00e9l\u00e9my\n|3\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |Guadeloupe\n|76\n|33\n|19\n|50\n|10\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |Mayotte\n|35\n|20\n|4\n|24\n|2\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |R\u00e9union\n|141\n|42\n|3\n|58\n|0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Subtotal Overseas France\n!364\n!148\n!43\n!193\n!17\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!90,676\n!31,267\n!7,004\n!24,932\n!8,598\n|}<br />Apart from the ''[[Petite couronne]]'',<ref name=\":18\" /> cases have been detected either by a late discovery or by a local infection in the following departments: [[Gironde]],<ref name=\":17\" /> [[Haute-Savoie]],<ref name=\":3\" /> [[Bas-Rhin]],<ref name=\":13\" /> [[Val-d'Oise]],<ref name=\":27\" /> [[H\u00e9rault]],<ref name=\":19\" /> [[Finist\u00e8re]],<ref name=\":20\" /> [[Lyon Metropolis]],<ref name=\":21\" /> [[C\u00f4te-d'Or]],<ref name=\":10\" /> [[Alpes-Maritimes]],<ref name=\":23\" /> [[Seine-Maritime]],<ref name=\":22\" /> [[Loire-Atlantique]],<ref name=\":24\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ouest-france.fr/pays-de-la-loire/nantes-44000/coronavirus-la-patiente-prise-en-charge-au-chu-de-nantes-est-une-medecin-en-vacances-a-la-baule-8a524926-5a18-11ea-b880-542ae49135b4|title=Coronavirus. La patiente prise en charge au CHU de Nantes est une m\u00e9decin en vacances \u00e0 La Baule|date=28 February 2020|website=Ouest-France|language=fr|access-date=27 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228143440/https://www.ouest-france.fr/pays-de-la-loire/nantes-44000/coronavirus-la-patiente-prise-en-charge-au-chu-de-nantes-est-une-medecin-en-vacances-a-la-baule-8a524926-5a18-11ea-b880-542ae49135b4|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Ain]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ledauphine.com/edition-genevois-chablais-bellegarde-pays-de-gex/2020/02/29/un-deuxieme-cas-de-coronavirus-dans-le-pays-de-gex|title=Ain. Un deuxi\u00e8me cas de coronavirus dans le Pays de Gex|website=ledauphine.com|language=fr|access-date=29 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229113048/https://www.ledauphine.com/edition-genevois-chablais-bellegarde-pays-de-gex/2020/02/29/un-deuxieme-cas-de-coronavirus-dans-le-pays-de-gex|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Landes (department)|Landes]],<ref name=\"auto2\" /> [[Charente-Maritime]],<ref name=\":26\">{{cite web|url=https://www.lci.fr/sante/en-direct-coronavirus-trois-personnels-de-sante-de-l-hopital-tenon-contamines-2143314.html|title=EN DIRECT \u2013 Coronavirus : trois personnels de sant\u00e9 de l'h\u00f4pital Tenon contamin\u00e9s|website=LCI|language=fr|access-date=29 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229112053/https://www.lci.fr/sante/en-direct-coronavirus-trois-personnels-de-sante-de-l-hopital-tenon-contamines-2143314.html|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mayenne]],<ref name=\":25\" /><ref name=\":25\" /> [[Ille-et-Vilaine]],<ref name=\":29\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ouest-france.fr/sante/virus/coronavirus/info-ouest-france-coronavirus-un-premier-cas-detecte-rennes-une-femme-de-pompier-hospitalisee-6758739|title=INFO OUEST-FRANCE. Coronavirus : un premier cas d\u00e9tect\u00e9 \u00e0 Rennes, une femme de pompier hospitalis\u00e9e|last=GRISOT|first=Paul|date=29 February 2020|website=Ouest-France|language=fr|access-date=29 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229172658/https://www.ouest-france.fr/sante/virus/coronavirus/info-ouest-france-coronavirus-un-premier-cas-detecte-rennes-une-femme-de-pompier-hospitalisee-6758739|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Morbihan]],<ref name=\":35\" /> [[Haut-Rhin]],<ref name=\"auto4\" /> [[Eure]],<ref name=\"auto5\" /> [[Sarthe]],<ref name=\"auto3\" /> [[Gard]],<ref name=\":38\" /> [[Dr\u00f4me]],<ref name=\":39\" /> [[Sa\u00f4ne-et-Loire]],<ref name=\":40\" /> all the departments of the region [[Hauts-de-France]], except the [[Nord (French department)|Nord]],<ref name=\"20minutes2730587\">{{cite web|url=https://www.20minutes.fr/sante/2730587-20200302-coronavirus-covid-19-desormais-present-toute-region-hauts-france|title=Le coronavirus est d\u00e9sormais pr\u00e9sent dans tous les Hauts-de-France|website=20 Minutes|language=fr|access-date=2 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302172701/https://www.20minutes.fr/sante/2730587-20200302-coronavirus-covid-19-desormais-present-toute-region-hauts-france|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and in the overseas territories of [[Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]] and [[Collectivity of Saint Martin|Saint Martin]].<ref name=\":33\" />\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/France medical cases}}\n\n== Simulation statistics ==\nSimulation studies helped convince the government that taking no action would result in large numbers of civilian casualties. In such a case between 30,000 and 100,000 more [[Intensive care unit|ICU]] beds would be required in the hospitals. In France there are 5,000 {{ill|reanimation service|fr|service de r\u00e9animation}} beds and 7,364 ICU beds. These simulations were provided by [[Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist)|Neil Ferguson]], epidemiologist at the [[Imperial College London]].<ref name=\"lemonde6033149\">[https://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2020/03/15/coronavirus-les-simulations-alarmantes-des-epidemiologistes-pour-la-france_6033149_3244.html Coronavirus : les simulations alarmantes des \u00e9pid\u00e9miologistes pour la France] 15 March 2020 ''Le Monde''. Retrieved 15 March 2020</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in France}}\n* Data and maps, frequently updated:\n** {{cite web |url=https://coronavirus-global.com/france |title=Coronavirus France updates and news |trans-title=Latest news and statistics of coronavirus in France. |access-date=4 April 2020 |language=English, French, Spanish, Portuguese, German, Italian, Swedish, Norwegian, Finnish, Estonian, Russian}}\n\n{{2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in France}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|France|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n{{#related:Emmanuel Macron}}\n{{#related:\u00c9douard Philippe}}\n{{#related:2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in France| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|France]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in France]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in France]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in France]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in France]]\n", "name_user": "S17003", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_France"}
{"title_page": "Institute of Science and Technology Austria", "text_new": "{{short description|Research institute in Austria}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = Institute of Science and Technology Austria\n|native_name =IST Austria\n|logo = Institute of Science and Technology Austria.svg\n|image = File:ISTA Maria Gugging Aussenansicht mit Lecture Hall.jpg\n|latin_name = \n|motto =\n|established = 2009\n|type = [[Public]]\n|endowment = \n|rector =\n|chancellor =\n|president = [[Thomas Henzinger]]\n|vice_chancellor = \n|principal = \n|dean =[[Nick Barton]] (Dean of the graduate school) \n|head_label = \n|head = 566\n|academic_staff = 461\n|students = 127\n|undergrad =\n|postgrad =\n|doctoral =\n|city = [[Klosterneuburg]]\n|state =[[Lower Austria]]\n|country = [[Austria]]\n|campus =\n|free_label = \n|free = \n|colours =\n|nickname =\n|mascot = \n|website = http://www.ist.ac.at/\n|staff = \n|faculty =\n|colors = \n|affiliations =\n}}\n\nThe '''Institute of Science and Technology Austria''' ('''IST Austria''') is an international research institute in [[natural sciences|natural]] and [[mathematical sciences]], located in Maria Gugging, [[Klosterneuburg]], 20&nbsp;km northwest of the [[Austria]]n capital of [[Vienna]]. It was established and inaugurated by the provincial government of [[Lower Austria]] and the federal government of Austria in 2009.\n\nIST Austria was established on the model of the Israeli [[Weizmann Institute|Weizmann Institute of Science]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.derstandard.at/story/2000109351426/ein-gruenderzentrum-fuer-das-ist-austria|title=Ein Gr\u00fcnderzentrum f\u00fcr das IST Austria - derStandard.at|website=DER STANDARD|language=de-AT|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> by its former president Israeli physicist [[Haim Harari]]. Like in the Weizmann Institute, scientists are encouraged to pursue their own goals and ideas not restricted by government or economic interest and all research themes are interdisciplinary.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lenotti|first=Carina|date=2007-07-11|title=Austria's science institute gathers steam|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=448|issue=7150|pages=112|doi=10.1038/448112b|pmid=17625527|issn=1476-4687|bibcode=2007Natur.448..112L|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nThe institute currently consists of 51 research groups and is expected to grow to about ninety research groups by 2026. Its graduate school offers an interdisciplinary doctoral program in the life, formal and physical sciences. As of June 2017, 127 students were enrolled.\n\nIn 2019 IST Austria was ranked 3rd among the world's best research institutions in the ''Nature'' normalized Index 2019, one rank behind the Weizmann Institute ranked 2nd.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ist.ac.at/en/news/ist-austria-no-3-among-the-worlds-best-research-institutes/|title=IST Austria {{!}} IST Austria No. 3 among the world's best research institutions|language=en|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{primary sources|section|date=January 2018}}\nThe idea of creating a scientific flagship organization for research and postgraduate studies at the highest level was proposed by Austrian physicist [[Anton Zeilinger]]<ref name=\"Lenotti pp. 112\u2013112\">{{cite journal|last=Lenotti|first=Carina|date=2007-07-12|title=Austria's science institute gathers steam|journal=Nature|publisher=Springer Nature|volume=448|issue=7150|pages=112|doi=10.1038/448112b|pmid=17625527|issn=0028-0836|bibcode=2007Natur.448..112L|doi-access=free}}</ref> in 2002 at the annual technology forum in [[Alpbach]]. After several studies about the feasibility of creating such an institute, a working group was formed in the Austrian federal ministry of education and science and the four [[States of Austria|provinces]] of [[Lower Austria]], [[Upper Austria]], [[Styria]] and [[Vienna]] put in bids to host the new institute. In 2005, the council of ministers decided to build the institute in [[Klosterneuburg]], [[Lower Austria]].\n\nIn 2006, an international group of three scientists including [[Haim Harari]], Olaf Kuebler and [[Hubert Markl]] were invited by the Federation of Austrian Industries to advise the establishment of the institute and create a road map for it. They published a report in June 2006 that became the foundation of IST Austria.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=2009|title=IST Austria Annual Report 2009|url=http://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Annual_reports/IST_AnnualReport_2009.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Harari|first=Haim|year=2006|title=Recommended steps towards the establishment of the Institute of Science and Technology - Austria|url=http://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Basic_documents/I.S.T.Austria_Report_Harari-Kuebler-Markl.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe federal law on the Institute of Science and Technology Austria was passed in May 2006<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=2006|title=Bundesgesetz \u00fcber das Institute of Science and Technology - Austria|url=http://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Basic_documents/I.S.T.Austria_Law_German.pdf|journal=Bundesgesetzblatt f\u00fcr die Republik \u00d6sterreich|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> and an agreement between the government of Lower Austria and the Federal government of Austria was reached in July.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=2006|title=Contract on the Establishment and the Operation of the Institute of Science and Technology Austria - Agreement between the Republic of Austria and the Federal State of Lower Austria, 2006|url=http://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Basic_documents/15a-Vereinbarung_E.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nPositions for the first president, professors and tenure track professors were advertised in 2007. Nick Barton was the first faculty to join. On December 4, 2008 computer scientist [[Thomas Henzinger]] was appointed as the first president of IST Austria effective September 1, 2009. In November 2016, he was reappointed as the president of IST Austria for a third 4-year term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ist.ac.at/en/news-media/news/news-detail/article/thomas-a-henzinger-reappointed-as-president-of-ist-austria-1/6/|title=IST Austria: Thomas A. Henzinger reappointed as President of IST Austria|last=Austria|first=IST|website=ist.ac.at|access-date=2016-11-30}}</ref>\n\nThe institute had its opening ceremony in 2009, recruited its first cohort of students in 2010 and by the end of that year reached more than 100 employees from 22 countries.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=2015|title=IST Austria Annual Report 2014|url=http://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Annual_reports/IST_AnnualReport_2014.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== First Evaluation ===\nAccording to the law, the institute is required to undergo an international and independent evaluation every four years. In January 2011, the Scientific Board organized the first independent evaluation of the new institute. The review panel consisted of six scientists who also had considerable experience in science management. The reviewers included two Nobel laureates and former or current presidents of distinguished research institutions. The panel broadly represented the natural and engineering sciences beyond the research areas that were present at IST Austria at the time.<ref name=\"evaluation_report_2011\">{{cite web|last=Baltimore|first=David|title=2011 Evaluation of the Institute of Science and Technology Austria|url=http://www.ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Eval_reports/110512_EvalReportEnFINALWeb.pdf}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, the evaluation committee came to the result that IST Austria is on its way to becoming a leading research institution with an international reputation and that the institute is about to set new benchmarks for both research and training that will not only be important on the national level but also within Europe generally and even more widely. The committee pointed out that the trajectory of development of all the elements of IST Austria is towards making an organization of clear excellence that will be recognized throughout the world, but continued governmental support is a necessary condition.<ref>{{cite web|last=IST Austria|first=press release|title=High-ranking evaluation committee gives IST Austria excellent grade|url=http://www.ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Press_release/2011_press_releases/110525_PA_PressConferenceEvaluationEn.pdf|accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Second Evaluation ===\nIn 2015, a second evaluation was carried out by an international review panel chaired by the Nobel laureate [[Roger D. Kornberg|Roger Kornberg]]. The panel consisted of six distinguished scientists including three [[Nobel Prize|Nobel]] laureates and a [[Turing Award|Turing awardee]]. The report was very positive, reading \"The next years will prove crucial if the IST Austria is to achieve the goal of international distinction. The IST Austria has made an excellent start, accomplishing the difficult task of starting from scratch and laying a foundation for future development, but the next step, rising to the top, will be even more difficult.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kornberg|first=Roger|year=2016|title=2015 Evaluation of the Institute of Science and Technology Austria (IST Austria)|url=http://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Basic_documents/2015_EvalReport_IST_Austria.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Funding ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2018}}\nThe long-term financial health of IST Austria relies on four different sources of funding: public funding, national and international research grants, technology licensing, and donations. From 2017 to 2026, IST Austria will receive up to \u20ac1.4 billion in public funding. Of those \u20ac1.4 billion, up to \u20ac990 million come from the federal government of Austria depending on the institute's ability to procure third-party funds. The state of Lower Austria provides the remaining \u20ac368 million in funding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://diepresse.com/home/bildung/universitaet/734375/14-Mrd-Euro-fuer-Eliteinstitut-in-Klosterneuburg|title=1,4 Mrd. Euro f\u00fcr Eliteinstitut in Klosterneuburg|date=2012-02-22|website=Die Presse|language=de|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\n== Organization ==\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2018}}\nThe governance and management structures of IST Austria guarantee the freedom from political and commercial influences. IST Austria is headed by the President, who is appointed by the Board of Trustees. More than half of the Board of Trustees is made up of international scientists, the remainder comprises members appointed by the federal government and the government of Lower Austria. The President is further advised by the Scientific Board.<ref>{{web cite|title=IST Austria Homepage: Board Structure|url=http://ist.ac.at/about-ist-austria/boards/|accessdate=2018-05-04}}</ref>\n\nThe first and recently reappointed President is Thomas A. Henzinger, a computer scientist and former professor of the University of California at Berkeley and the EPFL in Lausanne, Switzerland. He is supported by Vice President Michael Sixt, who oversees the operation of the scientific service units. The administration of IST Austria is led by Managing Director Georg Schneider.<ref>{{web cite|title=IST Austria Homepage: Management|url=http://ist.ac.at/about-ist-austria/management/|accessdate=2018-05-04}}</ref>\n\n==Graduate School==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2018}}\nThe institute's graduate school offers an interdisciplinary PhD program with six research tracks: biology, computer science, mathematics, neuroscience, physics, and data science and scientific computing. During the first year, students conduct three rotation projects in different research groups, before affiliating permanently with a research group and taking a qualifying exam. In the subsequent three to four years, students pursue research projects towards a PhD thesis.<ref>{{web cite|title=IST Austria Homepage: PhD Program|url=https://phd.pages.ist.ac.at/phd-program-overview/|accessdate=2018-05-04}}</ref>\n\n==Notable faculty==\nAs of May 2018, the faculty consists of 49 professors and assistant professors,<ref>{{cite web|last=IST Austria Website: Research Groups|title=Research Groups|url=http://ist.ac.at/research/research-groups/| accessdate=2018-05-04}}</ref>  including:\n\n* [[Nick Barton]], Evolutionary and Mathematical Biology\n*[[Krishnendu Chatterjee]], Theoretical Computer Science\n*[[Jozsef Csicsvari]], Systems Neuroscience\n* [[Herbert Edelsbrunner]], Algorithms, Geometry and Topology\n* [[Tam\u00e1s Hausel]], Geometry, Pure Mathematics\n* [[Thomas Henzinger]], Software Systems Theory\n* [[Robert Seiringer]], Quantum Statistical Mechanics, Mathematical Physics\n* [[Ga\u0161per Tka\u010dik]], Biophysics and Neuroscience\n\nAs of 2017, 38 ERC grants by the ([[European Research Council]]) have been awarded to IST faculty.<ref>{{web cite|title=IST Austria Annual Report 2017, page 4|url=https://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Annual_reports/IST_AnnualReport_2017.pdf|accessdate=2018-05-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613194146/https://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Annual_reports/IST_AnnualReport_2017.pdf|archive-date=2018-06-13|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official|http://www.ist.ac.at}}\n* [https://noe.orf.at/news/stories/2915278/ IST Austria: expansion \"pretty much on schedule\" (in German)]\n\n{{Coord|48|18|38|N|16|15|40|E|source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Austria]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2007]]\n[[Category:Scientific organisations based in Austria]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Austria]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Research institute in Austria}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = Institute of Science and Technology Austria\n|native_name =IST Austria\n|logo = Institute of Science and Technology Austria.svg\n|image = File:ISTA Maria Gugging Aussenansicht mit Lecture Hall.jpg\n|latin_name = \n|motto =\n|established = 2009\n|type = [[Public]]\n|endowment = \n|rector =\n|chancellor =\n|president = [[Thomas Henzinger]]\n|vice_chancellor = \n|principal = \n|dean =[[Nick Barton]] (Dean of the graduate school) \n|head_label = \n|head = 566\n|academic_staff = 461\n|students = 127\n|undergrad =\n|postgrad =\n|doctoral =\n|city = [[Klosterneuburg]]\n|state =[[Lower Austria]]\n|country = [[Austria]]\n|campus =\n|free_label = \n|free = \n|colours =\n|nickname =\n|mascot = \n|website = http://www.ist.ac.at/\n|staff = \n|faculty =\n|colors = \n|affiliations =\n}}\n\nThe '''Institute of Science and Technology Austria''' ('''IST Austria''') is an international research institute in [[natural sciences|natural]] and [[mathematical sciences]], located in Maria Gugging, [[Klosterneuburg]], 20&nbsp;km northwest of the [[Austria]]n capital of [[Vienna]]. It was established and inaugurated by the provincial government of [[Lower Austria]] and the federal government of Austria in 2009. \n\nIST Austria was established on the model of the Israeli [[Weizmann Institute|Weizmann Institute of Science]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.derstandard.at/story/2000109351426/ein-gruenderzentrum-fuer-das-ist-austria|title=Ein Gr\u00fcnderzentrum f\u00fcr das IST Austria - derStandard.at|website=DER STANDARD|language=de-AT|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> by its former president Israeli physicist [[Haim Harari]]. Like in the Weizmann Institute, scientists are encouraged to pursue their own goals and ideas not restricted by government or economic interest and all research themes are interdisciplinary.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lenotti|first=Carina|date=2007-07-11|title=Austria's science institute gathers steam|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=448|issue=7150|pages=112|doi=10.1038/448112b|pmid=17625527|issn=1476-4687|bibcode=2007Natur.448..112L|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nThe institute currently consists of 51 research groups and is expected to grow to about ninety research groups by 2026. Its graduate school offers an interdisciplinary doctoral program in the life, formal and physical sciences. As of June 2017, 127 students were enrolled.\n\nIn 2019 IST Austria was ranked 3rd among the world's best research institutions in the ''Nature'' normalized Index 2019, one rank behind the Weizmann Institute ranked 2nd.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ist.ac.at/en/news/ist-austria-no-3-among-the-worlds-best-research-institutes/|title=IST Austria {{!}} IST Austria No. 3 among the world's best research institutions|language=en|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{primary sources|section|date=January 2018}}\nThe idea of creating a scientific flagship organization for research and postgraduate studies at the highest level was proposed by Austrian physicist [[Anton Zeilinger]]<ref name=\"Lenotti pp. 112\u2013112\">{{cite journal|last=Lenotti|first=Carina|date=2007-07-12|title=Austria's science institute gathers steam|journal=Nature|publisher=Springer Nature|volume=448|issue=7150|pages=112|doi=10.1038/448112b|pmid=17625527|issn=0028-0836|bibcode=2007Natur.448..112L|doi-access=free}}</ref> in 2002 at the annual technology forum in [[Alpbach]]. After several studies about the feasibility of creating such an institute, a working group was formed in the Austrian federal ministry of education and science and the four [[States of Austria|provinces]] of [[Lower Austria]], [[Upper Austria]], [[Styria]] and [[Vienna]] put in bids to host the new institute. In 2005, the council of ministers decided to build the institute in [[Klosterneuburg]], [[Lower Austria]].\n\nIn 2006, an international group of three scientists including [[Haim Harari]], Olaf Kuebler and [[Hubert Markl]] were invited by the Federation of Austrian Industries to advise the establishment of the institute and create a road map for it. They published a report in June 2006 that became the foundation of IST Austria.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=2009|title=IST Austria Annual Report 2009|url=http://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Annual_reports/IST_AnnualReport_2009.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Harari|first=Haim|year=2006|title=Recommended steps towards the establishment of the Institute of Science and Technology - Austria|url=http://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Basic_documents/I.S.T.Austria_Report_Harari-Kuebler-Markl.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe federal law on the Institute of Science and Technology Austria was passed in May 2006<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=2006|title=Bundesgesetz \u00fcber das Institute of Science and Technology - Austria|url=http://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Basic_documents/I.S.T.Austria_Law_German.pdf|journal=Bundesgesetzblatt f\u00fcr die Republik \u00d6sterreich|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> and an agreement between the government of Lower Austria and the Federal government of Austria was reached in July.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=2006|title=Contract on the Establishment and the Operation of the Institute of Science and Technology Austria - Agreement between the Republic of Austria and the Federal State of Lower Austria, 2006|url=http://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Basic_documents/15a-Vereinbarung_E.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nPositions for the first president, professors and tenure track professors were advertised in 2007. Nick Barton was the first faculty to join. On December 4, 2008 computer scientist [[Thomas Henzinger]] was appointed as the first president of IST Austria effective September 1, 2009. In November 2016, he was reappointed as the president of IST Austria for a third 4-year term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ist.ac.at/en/news-media/news/news-detail/article/thomas-a-henzinger-reappointed-as-president-of-ist-austria-1/6/|title=IST Austria: Thomas A. Henzinger reappointed as President of IST Austria|last=Austria|first=IST|website=ist.ac.at|access-date=2016-11-30}}</ref>\n\nThe institute had its opening ceremony in 2009, recruited its first cohort of students in 2010 and by the end of that year reached more than 100 employees from 22 countries.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=2015|title=IST Austria Annual Report 2014|url=http://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Annual_reports/IST_AnnualReport_2014.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== First Evaluation ===\nAccording to the law, the institute is required to undergo an international and independent evaluation every four years. In January 2011, the Scientific Board organized the first independent evaluation of the new institute. The review panel consisted of six scientists who also had considerable experience in science management. The reviewers included two Nobel laureates and former or current presidents of distinguished research institutions. The panel broadly represented the natural and engineering sciences beyond the research areas that were present at IST Austria at the time.<ref name=\"evaluation_report_2011\">{{cite web|last=Baltimore|first=David|title=2011 Evaluation of the Institute of Science and Technology Austria|url=http://www.ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Eval_reports/110512_EvalReportEnFINALWeb.pdf}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, the evaluation committee came to the result that IST Austria is on its way to becoming a leading research institution with an international reputation and that the institute is about to set new benchmarks for both research and training that will not only be important on the national level but also within Europe generally and even more widely. The committee pointed out that the trajectory of development of all the elements of IST Austria is towards making an organization of clear excellence that will be recognized throughout the world, but continued governmental support is a necessary condition.<ref>{{cite web|last=IST Austria|first=press release|title=High-ranking evaluation committee gives IST Austria excellent grade|url=http://www.ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Press_release/2011_press_releases/110525_PA_PressConferenceEvaluationEn.pdf|accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Second Evaluation ===\nIn 2015, a second evaluation was carried out by an international review panel chaired by the Nobel laureate [[Roger D. Kornberg|Roger Kornberg]]. The panel consisted of six distinguished scientists including three [[Nobel Prize|Nobel]] laureates and a [[Turing Award|Turing awardee]]. The report was very positive, reading \"The next years will prove crucial if the IST Austria is to achieve the goal of international distinction. The IST Austria has made an excellent start, accomplishing the difficult task of starting from scratch and laying a foundation for future development, but the next step, rising to the top, will be even more difficult.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kornberg|first=Roger|year=2016|title=2015 Evaluation of the Institute of Science and Technology Austria (IST Austria)|url=http://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Basic_documents/2015_EvalReport_IST_Austria.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Funding ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2018}}\nThe long-term financial health of IST Austria relies on four different sources of funding: public funding, national and international research grants, technology licensing, and donations. From 2017 to 2026, IST Austria will receive up to \u20ac1.4 billion in public funding. Of those \u20ac1.4 billion, up to \u20ac990 million come from the federal government of Austria depending on the institute's ability to procure third-party funds. The state of Lower Austria provides the remaining \u20ac368 million in funding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://diepresse.com/home/bildung/universitaet/734375/14-Mrd-Euro-fuer-Eliteinstitut-in-Klosterneuburg|title=1,4 Mrd. Euro f\u00fcr Eliteinstitut in Klosterneuburg|date=2012-02-22|website=Die Presse|language=de|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\n== Organization ==\n{{refimprove section|date=January 2018}}\nThe governance and management structures of IST Austria guarantee the freedom from political and commercial influences. IST Austria is headed by the President, who is appointed by the Board of Trustees. More than half of the Board of Trustees is made up of international scientists, the remainder comprises members appointed by the federal government and the government of Lower Austria. The President is further advised by the Scientific Board.<ref>{{web cite|title=IST Austria Homepage: Board Structure|url=http://ist.ac.at/about-ist-austria/boards/|accessdate=2018-05-04}}</ref>\n\nThe first and recently reappointed President is Thomas A. Henzinger, a computer scientist and former professor of the University of California at Berkeley and the EPFL in Lausanne, Switzerland. He is supported by Vice President Michael Sixt, who oversees the operation of the scientific service units. The administration of IST Austria is led by Managing Director Georg Schneider.<ref>{{web cite|title=IST Austria Homepage: Management|url=http://ist.ac.at/about-ist-austria/management/|accessdate=2018-05-04}}</ref>\n\n==Graduate School==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2018}}\nThe institute's graduate school offers an interdisciplinary PhD program with six research tracks: biology, computer science, mathematics, neuroscience, physics, and data science and scientific computing. During the first year, students conduct three rotation projects in different research groups, before affiliating permanently with a research group and taking a qualifying exam. In the subsequent three to four years, students pursue research projects towards a PhD thesis.<ref>{{web cite|title=IST Austria Homepage: PhD Program|url=https://phd.pages.ist.ac.at/phd-program-overview/|accessdate=2018-05-04}}</ref>\n\n==Notable faculty==\nAs of May 2018, the faculty consists of 49 professors and assistant professors,<ref>{{cite web|last=IST Austria Website: Research Groups|title=Research Groups|url=http://ist.ac.at/research/research-groups/| accessdate=2018-05-04}}</ref>  including:\n\n* [[Nick Barton]], Evolutionary and Mathematical Biology\n*[[Krishnendu Chatterjee]], Theoretical Computer Science\n*[[Jozsef Csicsvari]], Systems Neuroscience\n* [[Herbert Edelsbrunner]], Algorithms, Geometry and Topology\n* [[Tam\u00e1s Hausel]], Geometry, Pure Mathematics\n* [[Thomas Henzinger]], Software Systems Theory\n* [[Robert Seiringer]], Quantum Statistical Mechanics, Mathematical Physics\n* [[Ga\u0161per Tka\u010dik]], Biophysics and Neuroscience\n\nAs of 2017, 38 ERC grants by the ([[European Research Council]]) have been awarded to IST faculty.<ref>{{web cite|title=IST Austria Annual Report 2017, page 4|url=https://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Annual_reports/IST_AnnualReport_2017.pdf|accessdate=2018-05-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613194146/https://ist.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Annual_reports/IST_AnnualReport_2017.pdf|archive-date=2018-06-13|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official|http://www.ist.ac.at}}\n* [https://noe.orf.at/news/stories/2915278/ IST Austria: expansion \"pretty much on schedule\" (in German)]\n\n\n{{Coord|48|18|38|N|16|15|40|E|source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Austria]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2007]]\n[[Category:Scientific organisations based in Austria]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Austria]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Institute_of_Science_and_Technology_Austria"}
